The problem is probably in client side validation. The client side validation of `\yii\validators\CompareValidator` is designed to compare two input fields but you have nothing to compare with. In your case probably the best option is to skip the client side validation for this rule and only use this rule during server side validation. To do that set `$enableClientValidation` property to false in your rule definition like this:
```php
public function rules()
{
    return [
        [
            &#39;STOCK&#39;,
            &#39;compare&#39;,
            &#39;compareAttribute&#39; =&gt; &#39;existences&#39;,
            &#39;operator&#39; =&gt; &#39;&lt;=&#39;,
            &#39;enableClientValidation&#39; =&gt; false,
        ],
    ];
}
```

Also having a method that returns some value in if branch and has no return in main branch is a bad practice and it invites bugs. In your `getExistences` you should return some default value (for example 0) or throw an exception when nothing is found by `findOne`.

